english:
  title: Letter to Minister Noh, the Registrar
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Recently I witnessed your appointment, and learning that my esteemed elder brother has been honored with the Left Minister's post and the royal favor, I bow in respect and joy.

    I reflect that while a nation possesses officials to investigate wrongdoing and the land harbors no hidden talent, this was difficult even in former ages—yet it is uniquely abundant in our court. Moreover, such men can censure the highest ministers above and reform all officials below. When I consider your abilities, they surely manifest perfect virtue.

    You, my esteemed Left Minister, possess the measured temperance of the Mean and embody the clarity of the Great Odes. Like a pillar sustaining the clear sky where no clouds rest upon the mountain peak, or autumn's radiance reflected in a pond where moonlight dwells—you have wandered through the halls of honor and brought brilliance to worthy governance. When you took on the burden of shared duty as prefect, you left behind exemplary rule. Soon summoned by imperial decree, you ascended to steward the celestial realm.

    Then joy shook the groves of scholars like wind through trees, and delight scattered like clouds across the ranks of brushes. Every tongue offered congratulations; no heart remained unmoved. The pearl of the spirit isles seemed to depart from beneath the chin; the jade of Jingshan waited to rest in your palm.

    Yet the Valley of Orioles kept spring hidden, and the Phoenix City fell to invaders. We could not witness the flourishing of Confucius's circle—only mourn the lingering calamities upon the Gate of Heaven. Now, traveling far from the imperial court, you have long served in the Censoriate. Already risen to a fair rank at court, your glory ascends to high office in the Bureau of Scrutiny. Your caution mirrors Fucius; your dignity matches Zheng Jin. This very moment you must inherit the fragrant dust of your predecessors.

    The Registrar, withdrawn for a time, climbed the slope with restless thoughts. Now hearing of your auspicious appointment brings some comfort to distant longing. Yet often my heart rushes to the crimson curtains, sharing in the same feelings. These lingering regrets shall only be resolved when heaven's workings are in hand—then all hearts will find contentment. Standing tall, awaiting the phoenix's edict, I reverently pray and gaze from afar, with sentiments too deep for words.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Left Minister' (左丞) was one of the highest administrative positions in the Silla court.
    - References to 'eight ministers' (八座), 'Censoriate' (憲府), and 'Bureau of Scrutiny' (肅機) reflect the structured bureaucracy of the period.
    - The allusions to Fucius and Zheng Jin invoke exemplars of official virtue and propriety.
    - The 'Valley of Orioles' and 'Phoenix City' refer to political turbulence and foreign threats facing the kingdom.
    - This letter demonstrates the refined court poetry style characteristic of Choe Chi-won's diplomatic correspondence.
